%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Factor Prices and Incomes %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Factor Prices and Incomes}

\begin{itemize}
  \item Goods and services are produced using four factors of production - labor, capital, land and entrepreneurship.
  \item Incomes are determined by the quantities of the factors used and by factor prices.
  \item Factor prices are the \emph{wage} rate earned by labor, the \emph{interest} rate earned by capital, the \emph{rental} rate earned by land, and the \emph{normal profit} rate earned by entrepreneurship. 
  \item \textbf{Derived demand} is the demand for a factor of production because it is \emph{derived} form the demand for the goods and services produced by the factor.
  \item The law of demand applies to factors of production just as it does to goods and services.
  \item The law of supply applies to factors of production just as it does to goods and services. The higher the price of a factor, other things remaining the same, the greater is the quantity supplied of that factor.
  \item The demand for and supply of a factor of production determines the equilibrium factor price and factor income.
  \item 
\end{itemize}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Labor Markets %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Labor Markets}
\begin{itemize}
  \item A firm's demand for labor is the flip side of its supply of output.
  \item The \textbf{marginal revenue product of labor} is the change in total revenue that results from employing one more unit of labor.
  \item As the quantity of labor increases the marginal revenue product decreases. In perfect competition the marginal revenue product decreases because the marginal product diminishes. In monopoly the marginal revenue product decreases because more labor is hire means more product is being created which means a firm must cut its price to sell the additional product.
  \item The margainal revenue product of labor determines the demand for labor.
  \item When marginal revenue product of labor equals the wage rate we maximize profit.
  \item Profit is maximized when, at the quantity of labor hired, \emph{marginal revenue product} equals the wage rate and when, at the output produced, \emph{marginal revenue} equals \emph{marginal cost}. Recall:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Marginal Revenue Product (MRP) = Marginal Revenue (MR) * Marginal Product (MP)
    \item MR = MRP / MP (The equation states that when profit is maximized, marginal revenue equals the wage rate divided by the marginal product of labor).
    \item MR = MC (Where MC is the marginal cost of labor).
  \end{itemize}
  \item Wage rates increase because demand increases by more than supply.
  \item Two conditions for Maximum Profit: \textbf{MR = MC} and \textbf{MRP = W}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Changes in Demand for Labor}
The demand for labor depends on three factors:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item The price of the firm's output.
  \item Other factor prices. \emph{The effect of a change in some other factor price depends on whether the factor is a substitute for or  a complement of labor.}
  \item Technology and capital. \emph{Computers replaced telephone operators, but increased the demand for electronics manufacture and programming.}
\end{enumerate}
